The Jubilee Party has started training the officials who will handle Friday&rsquo;s primaries countrywide.Senior regional directors working at Jubilee headquarters have been shuffled and deployed to take charge of the trainings in at least 30 counties.This follows the recruitment of county returning officers, presiding officers and polling clerks who will conduct the April 21 primaries.Jubilee regional director Steve Mwanga said the party will pull all stops to conduct free, fair and transparent nominations whose results will reflect the will of the Jubilee party members.He added that aspirants are expected to commit to the Code of Conduct that stipulates tough sanctions for perpetrators of violence during the primaries, which include disqualification.